                  <strong>CIO Alert</strong><br>
                  <strong>CIO.com May 26, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The computer scientist credited with inventing  the World Wide Web strongly condemned moves by U.S. broadband providers to  control their subscribers&rsquo; content, saying it threatens the Internet&rsquo;s greatest  strength: openness. Tim Berners-Lee on Tuesday said some Internet regulation is  needed but should be minimal. He said efforts to control content have  far-reaching impacts on other areas for users, such as decisions on voting and  development of democracy. <a href="http://www.cio.com/blog_view.html?CID=21369">...Full  Story</a></p>
