              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://computerworld.co.nz/news.nsf/0/8B9C94A6FE21255ACC25717D0002CCA2?OpenDocument" target="_hdl">Tagging data has business benefits,  web gathering told</a></strong><br>
                  <strong>Jeremy Kirk</strong><br>
                  <strong>ComputerWorld May 29, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Next-generation search technologies for  the internet can successfully be applied to companies, enabling them to  organise and find data on their own intranets. Businesses that realise the  importance of tagging and classifying their data will gain an advantage over  those that don&rsquo;t, says Clare Hart, an executive vice president at Dow Jones and  chair of Factiva, the company&rsquo;s subscription business news and information  service. <a href="http://computerworld.co.nz/news.nsf/0/8B9C94A6FE21255ACC25717D0002CCA2?OpenDocument">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.vnunet.com/financial-director/analysis/2156747/standard-issue" target="_hdl">Standard Issue</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Antony Harrington</strong><br>
                <strong>VNUNet.com May 26, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Large companies are spending millions to  harmonise technology standards and protocols throughout their organisations,  but they are still a long way from a truly integrated system....XBRL is being  developed by an international, non-profit consortium of approximately 450  organisations and already there are numerous implementations. The basic approach  is to provide a computer readable identifying &lsquo;tag&rsquo; for each individual item of  data. <a href="http://www.vnunet.com/financial-director/analysis/2156747/standard-issue">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.informationweek.com/news/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=188500573&subSection=All+Stories" target="_hdl">Feds Lead The XBRL Charge</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Elena Malykhina</strong><br>
                <strong>InformationWeek May 31, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Federal regulators usually aren't at  the forefront of technology adoption. But the folks in Washington who oversee  banks and financial services providers are spearheading the adoption of XBRL,  the Extensible Business Reporting Language, an emerging international standard  for the electronic transmission of business and financial information. However,  with their focus on using XBRL to file regulatory reports, financial services  firms are missing many of the benefits that the standard is supposed to  provide. <a href="http://www.informationweek.com/news/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=188500573&subSection=All+Stories">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style10"><strong>WSIS/Internet Governance</strong></p>
              <table width="508"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td colspan="2" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>[W]hat will happen to  the internet on 30 September 2006?</em></strong><em>&nbsp; [June 22,  2006]</em></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td width="46" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td width="455" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p>UKRegister.com's  Kieren McCarthy, discussing the expiration of ICANN's MOU to control the root  domain directories of the Internet&hellip;<a href="http://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/06/22/icann_marrakesh_preview/">Full  Story</a></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <table width="605"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>ICANN rides (or not) again:</em></strong><em> I  haven't been following this story closely enough to given an opinion on whether  the conclusions in the following story are on or off target, but it's worth a  read to get a feel for how many, and what types, of conflicts continue to exist  relating to ICANN's stewardship of the root directories for the Internet. With  the approaching expiration date (September 30) for the MOU under which ICANN operates  fast approaching, expect to see these disagreements play an increasingly  prominent place in the news.</em> </p></td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p align="center" class="style10"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/06/22/icann_marrakesh_preview/" target="_hdl">Will the internet die in September?</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Kieren McCarthy</strong><br>
                <strong>TheRegister.com June 23, 2006</strong>&nbsp;There will be much to discuss at  ICANN's Marrakech meeting which kicks off this Saturday, but one question rises  about all others: what will happen to the internet on 30 September 2006? ICANN  has its own agenda to discuss, but that agenda and what people actually want to  discuss are a little different. As is the fundamental issue that everyone at  that meeting should be talking about. This is our account of what is likely to  happen, why, and what it all means. <a href="http://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/06/22/icann_marrakesh_preview/">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.digitalopportunity.org/article/view/133998/1/1138" target="_hdl">Paper on future of internet  governance</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Atanu Garai</strong><br>
                <strong>DigitalOpportunity.org June 2, 2006</strong>&nbsp; In this paper...&quot;a  combination of domestic pressures and aversion of international regimes caused  the US government delegation to reject the [WSIS] proposal. As a result, WSIS  concluded without a constitutional moment for Internet governance. It may turn  out, though, to be a Pyrrhic victory for the United States. The calls for  internationalization of Internet governance will not subside and the US will  have to continue to fend off demands for a transfer of power. The opportunity  for Internet governance to be based on the values of the Internet community,  however, will likely not return.&quot; <a href="http://www.digitalopportunity.org/article/view/133998/1/1138">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
