              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.theage.com.au/news/Technology/China-walks-out-of-meeting-to-resolve-bitter-feud-over-world-wireless-encryption-standard/2006/05/30/1148754947518.html" target="_hdl">China walks out of meeting to resolve  bitter feud over world wireless encryption standard</a></strong><br>
                <strong>The Age/Melbourne June 11, 2006</strong>&nbsp;An international dispute over a  wireless computing standard took a bitter turn this past week with the Chinese  delegation walking out of a global meeting to discuss the technology....  &quot;In this extremely unfair atmosphere, it is meaningless for the Chinese  delegation to continue attending the meeting,&quot; the Standardization  Administration of China delegation said in a statement carried by the official  Xinhua News Agency....Steve Mills, the chairman of the IEEE Standards  Association Standards Board, said in a statement, China &quot;has lost another  valuable opportunity to constructively discuss the technical merits of the two  security amendments.&quot; Instead, Mills said, China continued &quot;to focus  its attention on complaints about the balloting process.&quot; <a href="http://www.theage.com.au/news/Technology/China-walks-out-of-meeting-to-resolve-bitter-feud-over-world-wireless-encryption-standard/2006/05/30/1148754947518.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://english.people.com.cn/200606/09/eng20060609_272428.html" target="_hdl">Chinese WAPI delegation calls for  diplomatic support after &quot;unfair treatment&quot;</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Xinhua News Agency</strong><br>
                <strong>Peoples Daily Online June 10, 2006</strong>&nbsp;A Chinese delegation  representing a China-made version of a networking technology has called for  diplomatic support after quitting an ongoing international meeting in Prague  due to &quot;unfair treatment.&quot; &quot;It has become necessary for the  Chinese government to give diplomatic support to the home-grown WAPI  technology,&quot; the delegation said on Thursday through an e-mail to Xinhua. <a href="http://english.people.com.cn/200606/09/eng20060609_272428.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <table width="605"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>Standard setting as a (relative)  &quot;love-in:&quot;</em></strong><em> ISO has not yet responded  to China's appeal of the rejection of WAPI and allegations of bad conduct by  Intel and others, but the air wars rage on. In this editorial, ZDNet.UK argues  that China ought to focus more on playing the game competitively than winning  by any means. Of course, the same advice would be well taken by all other  participants as well. The second article following is from People's Daily  Online, and indicates that if the Chinese have read the ZDNet.UK editorial,  they weren't persuaded. [Those that are particularly interested in following  the WAPI/WIFI story should note that the editorial includes a link to the full  38 page complaint filed by China with ISO.]</em> </p></td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://comment.zdnet.co.uk/other/0,39020682,39273634,00.htm" target="_hdl">Play up, China, and play the game</a></strong><br>
                  <strong>Editorial/Leader</strong><br>
                  <strong>ZDNet.UK June 9, 2006</strong>&nbsp;....There's no way that ISO would back a  wireless technology without giving it serious, thorough examination. That  wasn't possible with WAPI, it appears, as China has declined to release full  details. There was no way to check the algorithms for cryptographic strength or  for back doors, and such details as were known &mdash; its lack of backward  compatibility &mdash; would have harmed any proposal regardless of its source.... <a href="http://comment.zdnet.co.uk/other/0,39020682,39273634,00.htm">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://english.people.com.cn/200606/07/eng20060607_271737.html" target="_hdl">China sends delegates to voting  analysis meeting on wireless encryption standard</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Peoples Daily Online June 9, 2006</strong>&nbsp;China sent a group of 10  delegates on Tuesday to Prague for a resolution analysis meeting on the  wireless encryption standard concerning the Chinese WAPI and American  11i....China would make a 100 percent effort even if there is only a one  percent chance that WAPI would win....&quot;The monopoly force from the  American standard maker IEEE failed WAPI in the voting process,&quot; said  Huang. <a href="http://english.people.com.cn/200606/07/eng20060607_271737.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.informationweek.com/news/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=188700275" target="_hdl">China Fights For Its Wireless  Standard Against Intel-Backed 802.11i</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Elena Malykhina</strong><br>
                <strong>InformationWeek June 4, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Chinese officials say the approval  process for a wireless security standard was unfairly stacked against its WAPI.  It could be the start of more such disputes....Disagreements around standards  are likely to become more common as China asserts its influence as a buyer and  maker of technology and looks to give its electronics manufacturers any  advantage that may be had with homegrown standards. <a href="http://www.informationweek.com/news/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=188700275">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://english.people.com.cn/200605/29/eng20060529_269419.html" target="_hdl">China appeals to ISO against  Intel-dominated wireless encryption standard</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Xinhua News Service</strong><br>
                <strong>PeoplesDaily.com.cn June 1, 2006</strong>&nbsp;China has appealed to the  International Standard Organization (ISO) against American chipmaker Intel's domination  on encryption standard for wireless local area network (WLAN) equipment.... The  China BWIPS said in a statement available to Xinhua that it has collected 49  pieces of evidence proving its case against IEEE. &quot;The serious violations  are rare in ISO's standardization history,&quot; said the statement, adding  that IEEE &quot;unjustly&quot; and &quot;unfairly&quot; violated ISO rules  which misled many national bodies that voted on the new international standard. <a href="http://english.people.com.cn/200605/29/eng20060529_269419.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <table width="605"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>Better late than never:</em></strong><em> This article is actually over a month old, but I didn't run across it until  now. It remains timely, and I'm including it now because it's one of the most  thorough popular press reviews that I've seen of the commercial issues  surrounding China's drive to develop and deploy its own ITC standards.</em> </p></td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China_Business/HD13Cb05.html" target="_hdl">China and the art of (standards) war</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Indrajit Basu</strong><br>
                <strong>Asia Times Online May 31, 2006</strong>&nbsp;In the afternoon of January 10,  Huang Ju, China's vice premier, made a videophone call from the Science and  Technology Innovation Achievements Exhibition that was then being held in  Beijing. For the residents of Bijie county, to whom this call was made, it was  a simple call from the vice premier that conveyed New Year greetings. But for  the global telecom industry, it was an end to several years of anxious waiting.  &quot;I am impressed with the quality of the call,&quot; Huang said, and with  those words he put the Chinese government's official stamp of approval on the  locally developed third-generation (3G) technology that was used for the  demonstration. <a href="http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China_Business/HD13Cb05.html">...Full Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.cio.com/blog_view.html?CID=21560" target="_hdl">China's WAPI Not Going Down Without Fight</a></strong><br>
                  <strong>CIO Today May 31, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Chinese backers of the rejected WLAN  Authentication and Privacy Infrastructure (WAPI) wireless security protocol  have accused rivals of unethical behavior in a last-ditch attempt to revive  their standardization hopes. The semiofficial China Broadband Wireless IP  Standards Working Group (BWIPS) singled out the Institute of Electrical and  Electronics Engineers (IEEE), accusing the group of acting improperly during  the international standardization process. &quot;IEEE has committed unethical  and unjust activities trying to destroy WAPI by every means,&quot; it said. <a href="http://www.cio.com/blog_view.html?CID=21560">...Full Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://today.reuters.com/business/newsArticle.aspx?type=telecomm&storyID=nSHA66502" target="_hdl">France Telecom joins China 3G  standard alliance</a></strong><br>
                <strong>Reuters May 29, 2006</strong>&nbsp;SHANGHAI - France Telecom (FTE.PA: Quote,  Profile, Research) has joined an industry group promoting TD-SCDMA, China's  homegrown standard for third-generation (3G) mobile wireless services, in the  latest of the company's recent moves into China. France Telecom Beijing R&amp;D  Co.'s recent joining of the TD-SCDMA Forum makes it the first foreign telecoms  carrier to join the group, the official Xinhua news agency reported late on  Thursday. <a href="http://today.reuters.com/business/newsArticle.aspx?type=telecomm&storyID=nSHA66502">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
